SIMPLE: front
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Front
<hw>Front</hw> <pr>(fr⟦ucr⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>frant</ets> forehead, L. <ets>frons</ets>, <ets>frontis</ets>;
perh. akin to E. <ets>brow</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The forehead
or brow, the part of the face above the eyes; sometimes, also, the whole
face.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bless'd with his father's <qex>front</qex>, his mother's
tongue.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Grim-visaged war hath smoothed his wrinkled <qex>front</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>front</qex> yet threatens, and his frowns command.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The forehead, countenance, or personal presence, as
expressive of character or temper, and especially, of boldness of
disposition, sometimes of impudence; seeming; <as>as, a bold
<ex>front</ex>; a hardened <ex>front</ex></as>;</def>
<specif>hence,</specif> <def>an attitude and demeanor intended to
represent one's feelings, even if not actually felt; <as>as, to put on a
good <ex>front</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>With smiling <qex>fronts</qex> encountering.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The inhabitants showed a bold <qex>front</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The part or surface of anything which seems to look
out, or to be directed forward; the fore or forward part; the foremost
rank; the van; -- the opposite to back or rear; <as>as, the
<ex>front</ex> of a house; the <ex>front</ex> of an army</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Had he his hurts before?⟦br⟧
Ay, on the <qex>front</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A position directly before the face of a person, or
before the foremost part of a thing; <as>as, in <ex>front</ex> of un
person, of the troops, or of a house</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The most conspicuous part.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The very head and <qex>front</qex> of my offending.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>That which covers the foremost part of the head: a
front piece of false hair worn by women.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like any plain Miss Smith's, who wears s front.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs.
Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The beginning.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Summer's
<xex>front</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>All the works along one side of
the polygon inclosing the site which is fortified.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Phon.)</fld> <def>The middle of the upper part of
the tongue, -- the part of the tongue which is more or less raised
toward the palate in the pronunciation of certain sounds, as the vowel
<it>i</it> in <it>machine</it>, <it>e</it> in <it>bed</it>, and
consonant <it>y</it> in <it>you.</it> See Guide to Pronunciation,
⟦sect⟧10.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>The call boy whose turn it is to answer the call,
which is often the word ⟦ldquo⟧front,⟦rdquo⟧ used as an
exclamation.</def> <mark>[Hotel Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bastioned front</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a
curtain connerting two half bastions.</cd> -- <col><b>Front
door</b></col>, <cd>the door in the front wall of a building, usually
the principal entrance.</cd> -- <col><b>Front of
fortification</b></col>, <cd>the works constructed upon any one side of
a polygon.</cd> <au>Farrow.</au> -- <col><b>Front of
operations</b></col>, <cd>all that part of the field of operations in
front of the successive positions occupied by the army as it moves
forward.</cd> <au>Farrow.</au> -- <col><b>To come to the
front</b></col>, <cd>to attain prominence or leadership.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Front</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Front
<hw>Front</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or relating to the front or
forward part; having a position in front; foremost; <as>as, a
<ex>front</ex> view</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Front</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Front
<hw>Front</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fronted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fronting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To oppose face to
face; to oppose directly; to meet in a hostile manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You four shall <qex>front</qex> them in the narrow lane.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To appear before; to meet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Enid] daily <qex>fronted</qex> him⟦br⟧
In some fresh splendor.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To face toward; to have the front toward; to
confront; <as>as, the house <ex>fronts</ex> the street</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And then suddenly <qex>front</qex> the changed reality.</q>
<rj><qau>J. Morley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To stand opposed or opposite to, or over against as,
his house fronts the church.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To adorn in front; to supply a front to; <as>as, to
<ex>front</ex> a house with marble; to <ex>front</ex> a head with
laurel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yonder walls, that pertly <qex>front</qex> your town.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Front</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Front
<hw>Front</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To have or turn the face or front
in any direction; <as>as, the house <ex>fronts</ex> toward the
east</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frontage</ent>⟦br⟧
